{"title_page": "International Young Physicists' Tournament", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2018}}\nThe '''International Young Physicists\u2019 Tournament''', '''IYPT''', is one of the world's most respected and prestigious<ref name=\"Haskell\">[https://dx.doi.org/10.1119/1.880414 Hugh Haskell, Charles Britton, and Ronald Edge. A different kind of physics competition\u2014the IYPT]. The Physic Teacher 38, 1, 22 (Jan. 2000) {{ISSN|0031-921X}}</ref><ref name=\"Feder\">[https://dx.doi.org/10.1063/1.2169438 Toni Feder. High Schoolers Debate Physics at International Tournament. Physics Today, Vol. 58  of Issue 12, p. 31 (Dec. 2005)]</ref> annual [[physics]] competitions centered on 17 non-examination research problems that are published yearly in late July. During the tournament, discussion-based sessions called ''Physics Fights'' are conducted and the performances of the teams are judged by expert physicists.\n\nThe IYPT is a week-long event in which currently around 150 international pre-university contestants participate. The participants present and discuss their research projects at the events that share common features with thesis defense or scientific conferences. The teams switch roles and take floor as Reporters, Opponents and Reviewers, thus learning about [[peer review]] early on in their school years.\n\nThe concept was conceived in 1979 by Evgeny Yunosov and was run as the [[Russian Young Physicists' Tournament]], an event localised to Russia.  He went on to initiate the first IYPT in 1988.\n\n== Timeline table ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!No.\n!Venue\n!Host country\n!No. of<br />teams\n!No. of<br />countries\n!Gold winner(s)\n!Silver winner(s)\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 1988\n| 1st\n| [[Moscow]]\n|{{flag|Soviet Union}}\n| 31\n| 3<ref name=\"history-preprint\">[Detailed history of IYPTs in 1988\u20131993 (preprint) http://ilyam.org/Draft_IM_Detailed_history_IYPT_1988-1993.pdf]</ref>\n| Disputable<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| Disputable<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1989\n| 2nd\n| [[Moscow]]\n| {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n| 8\n| 7\n| {{flag|West Germany}},<br />{{flagicon|Bulgaria|1946}} [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]]\n| {{flagicon|Russian SFSR}} [[RSFSR]]-School 710, Moscow<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1990\n| 3rd\n| [[Moscow]]\n| {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n| 6<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| 5 *<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| {{flagicon|Russian SFSR}} [[RSFSR]]-School 542, Moscow<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| {{flagicon|Latvia|1990}} [[Latvian SSR]]-Riga,<br />{{flag|Netherlands}}<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1991\n| 4th\n| [[Moscow]]\n| {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n| 7<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| 6 *<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| {{flag|Hungary}}<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| {{flag|Poland}},<br />{{flagicon|Soviet Union}} Soviet Combined team<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1992\n| 5th\n| [[Protvino]]\n| {{flag|Russia|1991}}\n| 12\n| 10\n| {{flag|Belarus|1991}},<br />{{flag|Czechoslovakia}}<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n| {{flag|Netherlands}},<br />{{flag|Russia|1991}}<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1993\n| 6th\n| [[Protvino]]\n| {{flag|Russia|1991}}\n| 19\n| 11\n| {{flag|Georgia|1990}}\n| {{flag|Ukraine}},<br />{{flag|Hungary}}<ref name=\"history-preprint\" />\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1994\n| 7th\n| [[Groningen (city)|Groningen]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| 12\n| 11\n| {{flag|Czech Republic}},<br />{{flag|Russia}}\n| {{flag|Georgia|1990}}\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1995\n| 8th\n| [[Spa\u0142a]]\n| {{flag|Poland}}\n| 15\n| 12\n| {{flag|Germany}}\n| {{flag|Czech Republic}},<br />{{flag|Hungary}}\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1996\n| 9th\n| [[Tskhaltubo]]\n| {{flag|Georgia|1990}}\n| 13\n| 10\n| {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n| {{flag|Germany}},<br />{{flag|Georgia|1990}}-2\n|-valign=\"top\"\n| 1997\n| 10th\n| [[Cheb]]\n| {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n| 15\n| 11\n| {{flag